                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d335">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.5048/120: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wharton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-06T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 6, 1929—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>45. Your 59, November 4, midnight. Did President’s message carry any
                    recommendation that Liberia ratify the Slavery Convention of 1926? It is
                    believed that ratification during the present session of the legislature would
                    have a most favorable effect upon world opinion, particularly in view of the
                    important mention made of the Convention in the terms of reference for the
                    forced labor investigation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
